    <string name="soil_info_title">Identify your soil</string>
    <string name="soil_info_lehmboden">Roll moist soil into a thin sausage shape: if it holds without cracking and feels smooth and plastic → Loam soil.\n\nNutrient-rich, moisture-retaining, ideal for most vegetables. Compacts if worked too early in spring.</string>
    <string name="soil_info_sandboden">Squeeze moist soil and release: if it crumbles immediately, feels gritty and falls through your fingers → Sandy soil.\n\nWarms up quickly in spring but dries out fast. Add compost regularly and use mulch.</string>
    <string name="soil_info_tonboden">Roll soil into a long, thin sausage: if it works easily, feels very sticky and shines when rubbed → Clay soil.\n\nNutrient-rich but prone to waterlogging and hard to work. Adding sand improves structure.</string>
    <string name="soil_info_humusboden">Dark to black soil that is crumbly and loose with an intense earthy smell. A handful feels light and spongy → Humus soil.\n\nIdeal for almost all crops. Rich in organic matter.</string>
    <string name="soil_info_loessboden">Rub dry soil between your fingers: if it feels very fine and silky-floury (like flour) without sticking → Loess soil.\n\nLight brown, very fine-grained, deeply fertile. Can crust over during heavy rain.</string>
    <string name="soil_info_kalkboden">Drip a little household vinegar on the soil: if it fizzes noticeably → Calcareous soil.\n\nOften light grey to beige with whitish stones. Alkaline pH (above 7). Plants sensitive to iron deficiency may show chlorosis.</string>
    <string name="soil_info_moorerde">Dark, light, fibrous soil with a strong peat smell. Squeeze it like a sponge: it releases water → Peat soil.\n\nAcidic (pH 4–5), low in nutrients. Ideal for blueberries and rhododendrons. Found in lowland areas.</string>
    <string name="soil_info_mischboden">Soil can briefly be rolled into a sausage that then breaks apart easily. Neither particularly gritty nor sticky, medium water retention → Mixed soil.\n\nThe most common soil type in home gardens. A good basis for almost all crops.</string>
